👥 Day 06 — Linux Users & Groups Management

User and permission management is a core responsibility in DevOps and System Administration.

Today we will learn:

👤 Creating users
🔑 Managing passwords
👥 Managing groups
🛡️ Sudo access
🔒 Security basics
📌 Why Users & Groups Matter?

Linux is a multi-user operating system.

Users and groups help:

🔐 Secure systems
👥 Control access
🛡️ Protect files
⚙️ Manage permissions

In DevOps, proper access management is critical for production servers.

👤 1. useradd — Create New User
📌 Definition

Creates a new Linux user.

🛠️ Syntax
sudo useradd username
✅ Example
sudo useradd devops

Creates user:

devops
🔍 Verify User
cat /etc/passwd

🔑 2. passwd — Set User Password
📌 Definition

Used to set or change user password.

🛠️ Syntax
sudo passwd username
✅ Example
sudo passwd devops

System asks:

Enter new UNIX password:

👥 3. groupadd — Create Group
📌 Definition

Creates a new group.

🛠️ Syntax
sudo groupadd groupname
✅ Example
sudo groupadd developers

👤➕👥 Add User to Group
Command
sudo usermod -aG groupname username
✅ Example
sudo usermod -aG developers devops

🔍 Check User Groups
Command
groups username
✅ Example
groups devops

Output:

devops developers
❌ 4. userdel — Delete User
📌 Definition

Deletes a Linux user.

🛠️ Syntax
sudo userdel username
✅ Example
sudo userdel devops

🗑️ Delete User with Home Directory
sudo userdel -r devops

🛡️ 5. sudo — Super User Access
📌 Definition

sudo allows normal users to execute administrative commands.

🛠️ Example
sudo apt update
🔥 Why Sudo is Important?

Without sudo:
❌ Users can accidentally damage the system.

With sudo:
✅ Only authorized users can perform admin tasks.

👑 6. Switch User — su
📌 Definition

Switch from one user to another.

🛠️ Syntax
su username
✅ Example
su devops

🔍 7. Check Current User
Command
whoami
✅ Example Output
ubuntu
📂 Important User Files
File	Purpose
/etc/passwd	User information
/etc/group	Group information
/etc/shadow	Encrypted passwords

🧪 Hands-On Practice

Run these commands carefully:

sudo useradd devops

sudo passwd devops

sudo groupadd developers

sudo usermod -aG developers devops

groups devops

cat /etc/passwd

🔥 Real DevOps Scenario
Create Deployment User
sudo useradd deploy
Set Password
sudo passwd deploy
Give Sudo Access
sudo usermod -aG sudo deploy
🔍 Verify Sudo Group
groups deploy

Output:

deploy sudo

✅ User now has admin privileges.

🎯 Important Commands Summary
Command	Purpose
useradd	Create user
passwd	Set password
groupadd	Create group
usermod	Modify user
groups	Show user groups
userdel	Delete user
sudo	Admin access
su	Switch user

💡 Key Learnings

✅ Linux supports multiple users
✅ Groups simplify permission management
✅ sudo controls admin access
✅ User management is critical for security
✅ DevOps Engineers regularly manage users on servers
